 halls. Jobs considered appropriate for men and those for women were, she finds, sufficiently interdependent that the success of the action depended on both sexes cooperating. At the same time, with their livelihoods at stake, tensions between women and men often appeared.The AFL entered the twentieth century as the country's primary vehicle for unionized workers, and its attitude toward women formed the basis for virtually all later attempts at their organization. United Apart transforms conventional wisdom on the rise of the AFL by showing how its member unions developed their central beliefs about female workers and how those beliefs affected male workers as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2019) 0aLabor unionszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSexismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aStrikes and lockoutszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen labor union memberszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501727078423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501727078.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG